                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4 border-b-2 border-blue-200 pb-2">Reading Text</h2>
                    <div class="prose max-w-none text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                        <p><strong>Marc Filippino:</strong> Some critics say the Ukrainian government is becoming less democratic. Police have raided the homes of well-known public figures. They have also helped loyal people get government jobs. This has made activists, diplomats, and the media worried. At the same time, the country is trying hard to get weapons from Western countries for its war against Russia... Here to explain this is the FTâ€™s Ukraine correspondent, Chris Miller. Hey, Chris.</p>
                        <p><strong>Christopher Miller:</strong> Hey, Marc.</p>
                        <p><strong>Marc Filippino:</strong> So let's start with the police raids. Why are people so angry?</p>
                        <p><strong>Christopher Miller:</strong> Sure. Last Friday morning, the State Bureau of Investigation (SBI) was doing two different raids. One raid was in Kyiv, at the office and home of the former infrastructure minister, Oleksandr Kubrakov. Another raid was in the city of Kharkiv, at the family home of a famous anti-corruption activist, Vitaliy Shabunin. These men are accused of doing illegal things, but they both say the accusations are false. They believe the raids happened for political reasons.</p>
                        <p><strong>Marc Filippino:</strong> So these two men are part of a group that is unhappy with President Zelenskyy. Why are they unhappy with him?</p>
                        <p><strong>Christopher Miller:</strong> Well, they worry that Zelenskyy and his office have too much power and are using it in a bad way. They also worry about corruption during the war. Because everyone is focused on the war, some important changes needed for Ukraine to join the European Union have been forgotten.</p>
                        <p><strong>Marc Filippino:</strong> What will happen to Zelenskyy and the war if more people stop supporting him?</p>
                        <p><strong>Christopher Miller:</strong> We are seeing that the unity in Ukraine is starting to break. Part of this is because people are very tired. The war has been going on for three and a half years and it is causing many problems. This move towards a less democratic government increases the risk of problems inside the country. The security services warn this could be very bad.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Interactive Exercises Column -->
                <div class="space-y-8 h-screen overflow-y-auto pr-4">
                    <div class="activity-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-md">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">1. Useful Phrases</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                            <li><b>Becoming less democratic:</b> When a government gets more power and people get less freedom.</li>
                            <li><b>Well-known:</b> Famous or known by many people.</li>
                            <li><b>Worried:</b> Feeling nervous or anxious about something.</li>
                            <li><b>Accusations are false:</b> The claims against someone are not true.</li>
                            <li><b>For political reasons:</b> To get a political advantage, not for a fair reason.</li>
                            <li><b>Unhappy with:</b> Not pleased with someone or something.</li>
                            <li><b>Using power in a bad way:</b> Abusing authority.</li>
                            <li><b>Unity is starting to break:</b> People are not working together as much as before.</li>
                            <li><b>Causing many problems:</b> Creating difficulties.</li>
                        </ul>
